{"_id":"2PdwpOBWTfR1vFyl","name":"_Overview","content":"<p>Three Brothers' Barrow is a \"Location Module\"; it is designed to depict a Jarin tomb and a connected cave located in a pasture.  It is designed to depict an area within the Kingdom of Kaldor, on the island of Hârn in the <a href=\"https://columbiagames.com/harnworld/\">HârnWorld fantasy setting</a>; however, this keep and village could be adapted to exist anywhere in any fantasy setting.</p>\n<p>This module is based on the \"<a href=\"https://www.lythia.com/adventures/three-brothers-barrow/\">Three Brothers Barrow</a>\" fanon; please see @Compendium[hm-loc-tbb.journals.wHS5j24fIiUUn27k]{Credits} for more information.</p>\n<p><span style=\"color:#191813\">This module provides Gamemasters with a ready-made Jarin barrow tomb for Player Characters to explore. Three maps are included: a local map depicting the pasture where the ancient barrow has remained hidden until the present, interior plans for the barrow tomb itself, and interior plan for a small cave system that allows access to the hidden tombs. Additionally, stats are provided for a new type of Ivashu the PCs can encounter within the caves.</span></p>\n<p> </p>\n<h2>Using this module with Non-HârnMaster systems</h2>\n<p>Although this module is generally system-agnostic (with the exception of the Baethyr; see below), at various points references are made to HârnMaster game mechanics.  If using this module with a different system, you will need to convert these to your appropriate system mechanics (e.g., proficiency rolls, saving throws, etc.).</p>\n<p>If not using HârnMaster, the Baethyr actor will not be available. See @Compendium[hm-loc-tbb.journals.Nxvo40fDaWMup9Dz]{Baethyr: The Mind Flayer}; these details may be used to generate appropriate statistics for your game system.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<h2>Recommended Modules</h2>\n<p>The following modules, although not required, are highly recommended to enhance this module:</p>\n<p><strong>Compendium Folders: </strong>Due to the large number of journal entries in this module, these journal entries have been organized into sub-folders using Compendium Folders.  If Compendium Folders is not used, these will all show up as a single long list of Journal Entries in the compendium.  As long as you follow the links starting with the _Overview journal entry, it should not be necessary to navigate the compendium, but if you want to navigate through the Journal Entries yourself, having Compendium Folders will greately simplify this task.</p>\n<p><strong>Backgroundless Pins:</strong> The note icons all have a dark grey background; with this module, that background disappears.  This may increase your enjoyment of the maps.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<h2>Author's Preface</h2>\n<p>This location is an example of how simple ideas can be expanded into full adventures and even larger campaigns. In early 2007, while preparing for my then-new campaign, I was looking for something I could use as an introductory scenario for a manor-based group of characters. Looking through Aaron Kavli’s Hârn Encounters fanon (available on Lythia.com), I found a brief adventure hook (on page 43, if you’re curious) entitled “So infer Goeth the Flock.” Since my campaign’s setting (the manor of Erthen, in Vemionshire’s Lynnfana Hundred) had a lot of sheep, I thought the hook of a missing shepherd would be a good way to get the various PCs all involved in an impromptu rescue effort. As I sketched out the small cave the poor shepherd had fallen into, I added a few twists. There needed to be some sort of threat for the PCs to overcome, so I made up a monster, an Ivashu that dwelt in the caves.</p>\n<p>I thought that would be it, but then I happened to be looking at another piece of fanon, the excellent Naniom Bridge by Peter Fauconnier and Christophe Jaureguiberry, and got inspired again. The scenario “Brothers Awaiting” on page 30 of that article contained a wonderful idea for turpentine-soaked Jarin mummies guarding an ancient barrow tomb. I thought that such a tomb would make a great follow-up adventure to the rescue of the shepherd and altered my map to make the caves connect to a previously undiscovered barrow.</p>\n<p>As I was detailing the various chambers, I made a few rolls on the HârnMaster treasure generation tables and ended up with a golden torc. On the surface, this was way too rich a treasure to have drop into the PCs hands, and I almost discarded the idea. But then it occurred to me that the torc could be something more than just a treasure to be sold. I had always liked the tale of Owain the Martyr from the description of Zoben Keep (see Kaldor 52), and decided the tomb was meant for him and his two younger brothers, who sought vengeance for his murder by Ceorlan the Betrayer. The curse of the golden torc would play well into one of the recurring plotlines I had envisioned for my campaign.</p>\n<p>Whether you use this in a similar fashion or do something totally different, I hope it serves you well, and perhaps is the source of creative inspiration the way those earlier articles were a source for me.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<h2>Underground Hazards</h2>\n<p>PCs exploring underground environments face several potential dangers. Here are some suggestions for handling a few of them according to HârnMaster 3 rules.</p>\n<h3>Falling Objects</h3>\n<p>When falling from a great height, natural or man-made objects can easily cause harm. Such falling objects can be caused by rockslides, earthslides, avalanches, falling timber, subterranean collapses (cave-ins), and structural collapses of walls, ceilings, and other engineering.</p>\n<p>In general, falling objects inflict Blunt (B) impact to the location(s) struck. This is usually rolled on the High Aiming Zone on the Strike Location Table but may vary if the victim is not sitting or standing. If the falling object warrants it, Edged (E) or Point (P) impact might be substituted for (or applied in addition to) Blunt impact. Damage is based in part on velocity. The base damage is 1d6 for every 10’ (or portion thereof).</p>\n<p>This works well enough for a single object but in some cases, there are actually many objects affecting an area. A cave-in or collapsing building, for example, may result in an uneven distribution of falling debris.</p>\n<p>Earthslides (sand, dirt, loose gravel, 10,000 marbles, etc.), mudslides, and avalanches behave more like liquids than as solids. Generally, they cannot be dodged or outrun. Instead of blunt trauma, their effect is to force a Stumble check. A character who falls receives damage as if they had fallen a distance equal to the distance the slide carries them, using the material modifier appropriate to the substance, and rolling hit location for every 1d6. In other words, it might be possible to suffer 10d6, distributed evenly, and walk away merely bruised, or to suffer 10d6, all to one location, resulting in death or serious injury.</p>\n<h3>Bad Air</h3>\n<p>In enclosed, poorly ventilated areas, there is a risk of encountering oxygen-depleted air. This can be exacerbated by open flames, which consume available oxygen.</p>\n<p>In HM3 terms, oxygen deprivation can be represented as Fatigue levels that begin accumulating once the oxygen levels fall below that required for normal functioning. The rate at which these accrue is dependent on the number of people, their activity level, any open flames, and possibly other factors, so the GM must decide. As a general guideline, assume F1 per five minutes and adjust as needed. Once a character’s fatigue exceeds their END, they lose consciousness and further fatigue is treated as END loss. Once END reaches zero, the character is dead.</p>\n<h3>Cold and Wet</h3>\n<p>Without sunlight or fires to provide warmth, underground environments can be cold, particularly for characters who get wet, and it is often exceedingly difficult to stay dry underground. Characters suffering from exposure to cold, wet conditions will have to expend more of their energy on maintaining body heat.</p>\n<p>To reflect this, an extra fatigue level is added whenever a character normally accrues one. However, if the character is particularly chilled, such as in an underground river, GMs may increase this to F2 or F3 as they deem appropriate.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<section class=\"highlight\">\n<p>NOTE: The tomb and cave, although connected, are separate locations.  It is possible to discover the tomb first, then find the cave, or to find the cave first, then connect to the tomb.</p>\n</section>\n<p> </p>\n<h2>Area Map</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>@Compendium[hm-loc-tbb.journals.oVNtKDxm0asyJFcj]{[1] The Pasture}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[hm-loc-tbb.journals.AClPhIIJOyFFpN4k]{[2] Murrie’s Cave}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[hm-loc-tbb.journals.7mygd8JmdUIxhCFF]{[3] Barrow Entrance}</li>\n</ul>\n<p> </p>\n<h2>Murrie's Cave</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>@Compendium[hm-loc-tbb.journals.OrdFqJexaxyT4nap]{[C1] Cave Entrance}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[hm-loc-tbb.journals.mCXI63y3yIvzrg3S]{[C2] Pool}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[hm-loc-tbb.journals.yVgMl07dI3KUrAoA]{[C3] The Stream}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[hm-loc-tbb.journals.5vpQjC81I86piD7Q]{[C4] Debris}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[hm-loc-tbb.journals.q0Cdjo0cVdLV8clt]{[C5] Tomb Collapse}</li>\n</ul>\n<p> </p>\n<h2>The Barrow</h2>\n<p>For additional information, see @Compendium[hm-loc-tbb.journals.8QoHIul1OwcPq54x]{Note on the Alignment of the Tomb}.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>@Compendium[hm-loc-tbb.journals.mjgllaZy9Ydd2lJ8]{[T1] Sealed Entrance}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[hm-loc-tbb.journals.RC3e0OXHh8thS7wu]{[T2] Passage}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[hm-loc-tbb.journals.A91GH9AcQq0v8k6c]{[T3] Main Chamber}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[hm-loc-tbb.journals.rbviCI66eoIK93h9]{[T4a] Wealthy Warrior}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[hm-loc-tbb.journals.REm6KYZZdpPRSpiw]{[T4b] The Skull}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[hm-loc-tbb.journals.a2WFwJYHnygMeokf]{[T4c] Collapsed Tomb}</li>\n</ul>\n<p> </p>\n<h2>Adventure Hooks</h2>\n<h3>The Good Shepherd</h3>\n<p>While going about their daily business if they are residents of the manor, or simply traveling through, the PCs will be approached by a Kaldorin sheepdog (see Dogs 6 for details and HM3 stats) that is clearly trying to get their attention. If they pay attention, the dog will lead them to a nearby pasture where a flock of sheep is milling about in a muddy ravine with no shepherd evident. If the PCs are locals, they may recognize the dog as belonging to a young shepherd boy named Murrie; otherwise, they will likely be able to infer as much.</p>\n<p>The recent heavy rains caused a small sinkhole to open up in the ravine. One of the ewes got stuck in the small hole, and when Murrie tried to free it, the hole opened further, sending him, the ewe, and a mass of mud and stone into the cave below. Murrie is either dead or unconscious, at the GM’s discretion, but PCs won’t be able to tell without descending into the cave themselves, and that will in turn lead them to notice the distinct odor of turpentine, something odd for a cave.</p>\n<h3>Bring Me the Beast’s Head!</h3>\n<p>If the PCs encounter the Ivashu during their search for Murrie, the encounter might end with the creature still at large in the cave. The local lord will not want a dangerous beast running loose on his manor and may offer the PCs a reward to slay or drive it away.</p>\n<h3>The Barrow</h3>\n<p>Eventually, any exploration of Murrie’s Cave will lead to the discovery of the barrow. This could be relatively uneventful, or the tomb might contain one or more restless spirits that need to be quieted. Either way, the identification of the barrow lords may lead to further adventures, including the resolution of a potentially cursed treasure.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<h2>Denizens</h2>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:5em\">Name</td>\n<td>Journal Entry</td>\n<td>HârnMaster Actor</td>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:5em\">Baethyr</td>\n<td>@Compendium[hm-loc-tbb.journals.Nxvo40fDaWMup9Dz]{Baethyr: The Mind Flayer}</td>\n<td>@Compendium[hm-loc-tbb.actors.LgSUIAx1RNcDJE9Y]{Baethyr}</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p> </p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"qrblv55YbGxLkaKf":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.hm-loc-tbb.journals.CvVfl7XkgLPX3Hb9"},"scene-packer":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.gkIMk3HBNgsBdANu","hash":"9784aef8fea0dc87ec533dfbe7954c24b0ff1751"},"cf":{"id":null,"path":"Three Brothers Barrow","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"5vpQjC81I86piD7Q","name":"[C4] Debris","content":"<p>The passage rises along a series of step-like ledges. At this point, a mass of debris is scattered around the base of a steep slope. Mixed with the rubble are human remains and various artifacts that may be identifiable as grave goods, such as broken pottery, a few weapons, and animal bones. While much of this is far beyond use, the GM can include one or more items of value or interest, if desired. The odor of turpentine is stronger here, and the artifacts have clearly been deposited here after sliding down the slope.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"qrblv55YbGxLkaKf":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":800000},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.hm-loc-tbb.journals.GeNpJfYuY5qWhSXV"},"scene-packer":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.05LNRnaFTjIdQ8mB","hash":"c09b3a35ce4998cbbed8d0066aedcb682d30a218"},"cf":{"id":"temp_20qazfcekn","path":"Three Brothers Barrow#/CF_SEP/Murrie's Cave","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"7mygd8JmdUIxhCFF","name":"[3] Barrow Entrance","content":"<p>The surface entrance to Three Brothers Barrow is depicted on the GM local map above. However, when first explored, this remains concealed under a layer of dirt and grass as a part of the hillside.</p>\n<p>See @Compendium[hm-loc-tbb.journals.8QoHIul1OwcPq54x]{Note on the Alignment of the Tomb}.</p>\n<p> </p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"qrblv55YbGxLkaKf":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":600000},"scene-packer":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.AE2FNNqmBoeQjmKA","hash":"79c6af10a766096ba448a68c70bcb5897825442b"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.hm-loc-tbb.journals.EkJkEzEv3QiOs7kn"},"cf":{"id":"temp_26dq2y78fg8","path":"Three Brothers Barrow#/CF_SEP/Pasture","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"8QoHIul1OwcPq54x","name":"Note on the Alignment of the Tomb","content":"<p>The axis of the tomb is aligned with the winter solstice. While this may not become evident to PCs exploring the barrow for the first time, the rays of the setting sun on that day (1st Ilvin) would be perfectly framed by the opening of the tomb (assuming it is unsealed and the earth covering it has been excavated). The sunlight shining into the depths of the tomb would illuminate a section of the rear wall, revealing a pattern only visible in natural light. Finding the corresponding pattern on the decorations in the tomb will allow the discovery of a hidden compartment. This can be the hiding place for whatever treasure or clue best suits the GM’s campaign.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"qrblv55YbGxLkaKf":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.hm-loc-tbb.journals.QnfICimOYazRSQtS"},"scene-packer":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.ryHC61KJm2xxxX5j","hash":"492ddd54b26adf8bd5924c806c6719c3fe18c71f"},"cf":{"id":null,"path":"Three Brothers Barrow","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"A91GH9AcQq0v8k6c","name":"[T3] Main Chamber","content":"<p>The main chamber of the barrow is square, with a wide alcove on each wall featuring an opening to a side burial chamber. Four stout pine logs support the 12-foot peaked stone ceiling. With the passage of time, the pine resin oozing from the logs has left a residue around their bases and a powerful odor of turpentine. The floor of the chamber is painted in a detailed spiral with four smaller spirals around each of the columns. Within the spiral design are various renderings of men and beasts, all traveling towards the center where a serpent encircles Nolomar, the sun. The walls are decorated with stylized scenes of woodland, rivers, and mountains, while the ceiling is adorned with a pattern of stars around a light-colored disk that probably represents Yael, the moon. A brass brazier stands before each of the side chambers, still filled with ancient unlit charcoal and aromatic herbs.</p>\n<p>The braziers in the main chamber can be lit without much trouble, but doing so without making provision for ventilation may deplete the oxygen in the barrow and fill it with the smoke of aromatic herbs, including Fletharasha (see Herblore 11 and Potions 12). A well-concealed compartment in the floor can be opened by those who are aware of it (see @Compendium[hm-loc-tbb.journals.8QoHIul1OwcPq54x]{Note on the Alignment of the Tomb}).</p>\n<h2>Burial Chambers</h2>\n<p>Three side chambers are accessible from the main chamber. Each is a step below the level of the main chamber and has a low ceiling supported by heavy pine crossbeams. The walls of each are carved and painted with swirling Jarin designs and depictions of fanciful beasts. The chambers contain a bier for the deceased and an assortment of grave goods. Bowls, jars, and other containers once held food and drink that is now dust and residue. The tattered remnants of once- fine clothing, as well as carpet or tapestry, speak to the wealth and importance of those interred here.</p>\n<p>Ornate spears, shields, and other weapons, intact but brittle with age, are arrayed around the chambers and on the biers.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>@Compendium[hm-loc-tbb.journals.rbviCI66eoIK93h9]{[T4a] Wealthy Warrior}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[hm-loc-tbb.journals.REm6KYZZdpPRSpiw]{[T4b] The Skull}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[hm-loc-tbb.journals.a2WFwJYHnygMeokf]{[T4c] Collapsed Tomb}</li>\n</ul>\n<p> </p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"qrblv55YbGxLkaKf":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":600000},"scene-packer":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.KdhsJU6oRGqQL5AO","hash":"948445e2a8fa545d177c1097c02f408a85b1b552"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.hm-loc-tbb.journals.xJ4JS0xwFdTw02P9"},"cf":{"id":"temp_slr7zci5iw","path":"Three Brothers Barrow#/CF_SEP/Tomb","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"AClPhIIJOyFFpN4k","name":"[2] Murrie’s Cave","content":"<p>The only access to the cave is via a small sinkhole that has opened up during the recent heavy rains. The opening was initially fairly small, but unstable. When one of the ewes became stuck in the opening and Murrie weight caused the saturated soil to collapse, expanding the opening to its present size. Murrie, the ewe, and a mass of mud and loose stone were dropped into the cavern below. Any PCs entering the cave to search for the missing shepherd will be the first humans to explore it.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"qrblv55YbGxLkaKf":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":400000},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.hm-loc-tbb.journals.En6wYSfuBGAiouo7"},"scene-packer":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.yTIjBSprPmTcaHL7","hash":"17d37496293f15937b5872783854c62d97ac5fcc"},"cf":{"id":"temp_26dq2y78fg8","path":"Three Brothers Barrow#/CF_SEP/Pasture","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"Nxvo40fDaWMup9Dz","name":"Baethyr: The Mind Flayer","content":"<p>The Baethyr is an aquatic serpentine Ivashu measuring six to eight feet in length and eight to ten inches thick. Its scales are a dark gray coloration with an irregular pattern of dark red and violet along its underside. A series of small horn-like protrusions runs along its jaw, while a single horn juts upward several inches from the top of its skull. The Baethyr’s small dark eyes are difficult to pick out from its scales.</p>\n<p>Because it spends most of its time underground, the Baethyr’s vision is relatively poor. It possesses excellent hearing, however, and can detect movement, especially in water. The Baethyr can also detect scents through receptors in its forked tongue, allowing it to identify and track prey.</p>\n<p>The Baethyr has sharp teeth and can bite if necessary. However, it prefers to employ its psionic talent, Mental Bolt, to subdue prey. It usually feeds on fish but will sometimes emerge from its underground lair to prey on small animals, stunning them helpless before devouring them whole. The Baethyr will generally seek to avoid larger creatures, including humans, but will not hesitate to defend itself if it is cornered.</p>\n<p>Survivors of the Baethyr’s psionic attack describe a sudden, devastating headache (akin to a migraine), often accompanied by dizziness and nausea. Victims frequently experience what may seem like flashes of lightning at the edges of their vision, and many lose consciousness.</p>\n<p>The Baethyr that dwells in Murrie’s Cave is able to navigate the flooded portions of the cave network with ease, allowing it to escape into areas a human cannot access, as well as to enter and exit the caves through nearby underwater openings.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"qrblv55YbGxLkaKf":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":1000000},"scene-packer":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.PLSGzMYST2tfhHkZ","hash":"f362021d35920e0227a168fb96bb813402d4fffa"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.hm-loc-tbb.journals.geLYt4LWnzj3qhZr"},"cf":{"id":null,"path":"Three Brothers Barrow","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"OrdFqJexaxyT4nap","name":"[C1] Cave Entrance","content":"<p>Recent heavy rains have caused a small sinkhole to open, allowing access to the cave from the surface. The sinkhole is irregular in shape, approximately six feet by three, and very unstable. Attempts to climb in or out are penalized by the instability as well as the wet, muddy conditions. The sinkhole descends fourteen feet before opening into the cavern below. Directly beneath the opening is a mass of flowstone, sloping down to the underground stream that fills the cavern to an average depth of two feet. Rubble from the sinkhole litters the bottom of the slope, along with a dead sheep. A shepherd’s crook can be found partly covered by the debris.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"qrblv55YbGxLkaKf":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":200000},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.hm-loc-tbb.journals.hrQkL5FGNWso6hjp"},"scene-packer":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.gSTm8pjFwJh7n4UB","hash":"0c6c00718362f712f90648bdf6995cf0eb2784cc"},"cf":{"id":"temp_20qazfcekn","path":"Three Brothers Barrow#/CF_SEP/Murrie's Cave","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"RC3e0OXHh8thS7wu","name":"[T2] Passage","content":"<p>A long, gently sloping tunnel descends to the barrow’s main chamber. The floor is painted with a serpent design, while the walls depict scenes from the lives of the tomb’s occupants, three warrior brothers. PCs with Folklore skill may be able to glean clues to their identities. If the restless spirits of any of the Three Brothers linger in the tomb, the paintings may provide helpful guidance in dealing with them.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"qrblv55YbGxLkaKf":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":400000},"scene-packer":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.8HhVzIq9ckTtRlM0","hash":"5eb6c35ed82d4c9f8561a620b7674a005e13df96"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.hm-loc-tbb.journals.yyNuVWl0OwEeLPlG"},"cf":{"id":"temp_slr7zci5iw","path":"Three Brothers Barrow#/CF_SEP/Tomb","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"REm6KYZZdpPRSpiw","name":"[T4b] The Skull","content":"<p>A skull is all that remains of what must have been a very important warrior. A golden torc (10 oz.) rests on the bier alongside the skull and a few weapons.</p>\n<p>PCs with Folklore may know that when Owain the Martyr (see Tontury Lake 2) was betrayed and murdered by Ceorlan, the Prince of Arwn, Owain’s golden torc was taken by one of Ceorlan’s men. According to the legend, the torc is cursed and great misfortune will befall any who possess it unless they are the rightful ruler of Darlen. Although there is no conclusive evidence that there ever was an actual torc, most Kaldorans believe it exists. The tale is popular and is periodically updated; it seems the torc has been changing hands for centuries, trying to find its way back to its rightful owner.</p>\n<p>If the skull is truly that of Owain the Martyr, are the PCs willing to risk the curse to obtain the priceless artifact?</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"qrblv55YbGxLkaKf":3},"flags":{"entityorder":{"order":400000},"scene-packer":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.gwKHmJ2oHAPNdhvs","hash":"6d56ce831566dde281aff1d780696b2103fb8101"},"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.hm-loc-tbb.journals.1ted7kmikxfM4buC"},"cf":{"id":"temp_slr7zci5iw","path":"Three Brothers Barrow#/CF_SEP/Tomb","color":"#000000"}}}
